"analysis": "We computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and counted anomalies inside the incident window. Results show many db_* series (db_001..db_004, etc.) with anomalies starting at the very beginning of the window (2020-05-28 00:30:00 CST+0800). There is also os_007 Disk_rd_ios flagged. The previous anomaly counts double-counted points when p95==p5 (e.g., equality counted as both high and low). From that view, DB components are the dominant anomaly candidates and anomalies appear simultaneous across many DB KPIs and DB instances at 00:30. To proceed we must (1) de-duplicate anomaly detections so each timestamp is counted once per series, (2) aggregate anomalies up to the component level to find which components have the most unique anomalous timestamps and how many KPIs are impacted, and (3) get earliest anomaly times per component to locate occurrence time. This will narrow candidates for trace analysis.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Recompute anomalies using metric.csv and the same incident window (epoch start=1590597000, end=1590598800). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 from the full series. Then, within the incident window mark a row as anomalous if value >= P95 OR value <= P5 (but count each row at most once even if both conditions true). Next aggregate to component (cmdb_id) level: for each cmdb_id compute total_unique_anomalous_points_in_window (count distinct timestamps that are anomalous across any KPI), number_of_kpis_with_any_anomaly, total_points_in_window (all KPI rows in window for that cmdb_id), and earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (min timestamp of anomalous points). Return a compact table of the top 20 cmdb_id ranked by total_unique_anomalous_points_in_window with these columns and also return the overall number of components with at least one anomalous point and total anomalous points across all components. Limit output to top 20 rows." }

{
"analysis": "From metric analysis: many DB instances (db_001..db_013, etc.) and several OS nodes exhibited widespread simultaneous metric anomalies starting at the incident window start (2020-05-28 00:30:00 CST+0800). DB-specific KPIs such as Hang, Row_Lock and MEM_Total show consistent anomalous values across many DB components at the same earliest timestamp. From trace analysis: all docker containers (docker_001..docker_004 etc.) show pervasive trace anomalies (many error_rate traces) beginning at the same time. This pattern (clients/containers showing increased trace errors while DB instances show many KPI faults simultaneously) suggests the failure originated at the database layer and propagated to clients, rather than originating in the containers. The DB KPI 'Hang' being 1 across many DBs at 00:30 is a strong signal that DB processes became unavailable (hang/closed). To confirm the root cause component and exact occurrence time, we must verify the Hang KPI time series for each DB instance in the incident window (identify earliest timestamp per DB when Hang indicates failure, and check the length of the consecutive fault to ensure this is a sustained fault, not isolated spikes). This will let us identify the root cause component(s), the root cause occurrence datetime (first Hang==1), and support the underlying reason (db close/hang).",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv, filter rows for cmdb_id that begin with 'db_' and kpi_name equal to 'Hang'. Within the incident window (epoch start=1590597000, end=1590598800), for each db_* component compute and return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, total_points_in_window (for Hang), number_of_points_where_Hang_equals_1, earliest_timestamp_in_window_where_Hang_equals_1, latest_timestamp_in_window_where_Hang_equals_1, longest_consecutive_run_length_of_Hang_equal_1_within_window. Return rows for all db_* components sorted by earliest_timestamp (ascending) and limit to top 50 rows. Also return the total number of db_* components that had any Hang==1 in the window and the overall earliest Hang==1 timestamp across all db_* components. Keep outputs compact." }

